  "prompt": "How hard is it to break Pyrex?",
  "response": "Pyrex is known for its durability and resistance to thermal shock, but it is not indestructible. Here are some factors that affect how hard it is to break Pyrex:\n\n1. **Thermal Shock**: Pyrex is designed to withstand significant temperature changes, but sudden extreme changes can still cause it to break. For example, moving a Pyrex dish directly from the freezer to a hot oven can cause it to shatter.\n\n2. **Physical Impact**: Dropping Pyrex or hitting it with a hard object can easily cause it to break. Despite its strength, it is still made of glass and can shatter upon impact.\n\n3. **Surface Imperfections**: Scratches or chips on the surface of Pyrex can weaken it over time, making it more susceptible to breaking under stress or temperature changes.\n\n4. **Manufacturing Variations**: Not all Pyrex products are created equal. Some may have slight imperfections or variations in thickness that can affect their durability.\n\n5. **Type of Pyrex**: There are different types of Pyrex products, some of which may be more resistant to breaking than others. For example, Pyrex made with borosilicate glass is generally more durable than those made with soda-lime glass.\n\nIn summary, while Pyrex is quite resilient, it can still break if subjected to significant thermal shock, physical impact, or if it has surface imperfections. Proper care and handling can help minimize the risk of breakage.",
